Ralf Hütter (born 20 August 1946) is a German musician and composer best known as the lead singer and keyboardist of Kraftwerk, which he founded with Florian Schneider in 1969.
On May 12, 2021, Kraftwerk was announced as one of the inductees of the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame.
Hütter was born on 20 August 1946 in Krefeld, Germany.
The band members took up cycling when recording the album The Man-Machine in the late 1970s.
At the time this did not happen, but the project eventually was released as Tour de France Soundtracks in 2003.
Hütter was involved in a serious cycling accident in May or June 1982, during the initial period of recording for the 1986 album Electric Café.
